04678nam a22005415i 9781501740602DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20191991nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017406027 a10.7591/97815017406022doi  a(DE-B1597)527430  a(OCoLC)1102795188  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX1533.T69 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a282/.44545/09022201 aFarmer, Sharon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommunities of Saint Martin :bLegend and Ritual in Medieval Tours /cSharon Farmer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (378 p.) :b12 b&w halftones, 5 tables, 6 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Martin's Town: From Unity to Duality -- tIntroduction -- t1. Martinopolis (ca. 37I-I050) -- t2. Excluding the Center: Monastic Exemption and Liturgical Realignment in Tours -- tPART 2. Marmoutier -- tIntroduction -- t3. History, Legitimacy, and Motivation in Marmoutier's Literature for the Angevins -- t4. Marmoutier and the Salvation of the Counts of Blois -- t5. Individual Motivation, Collective Responsibility: Reinforcing Bonds of Community -- t6. Preservation through Time: Historical Consciousness at Marmoutier -- tPART 3. The Chapter of Saint-Martin -- tIntroduction -- t7. The Corporate Identity of the Canons of Saint-Martin -- t8. Saint Martin's Diocese: The Appropriation of Episcopal Symbols -- t9. Martin's New Town: Dominance and Resistance in Chateauneuf -- tConclusion -- tSource Appendix -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSharon Farmer here investigates the ways in which three medieval communities-the town of Tours, the basilica of Saint-Martin there, and the abbey of Marmoutier nearby-all defined themselves through the cult of Saint Martin. She demonstrates how in the early Middle Ages the bishops of Tours used the cult of Martin, their fourthcentury predecessor, to shape an idealized image of Tours as Martin's town. As the heirs to Martin's see, the bishops projected themselves as the rightful leaders of the community. However, in the late eleventh century, she shows, the canons of Saint-Martin (where the saint's relics resided) and the monks of Marmoutier (which Martin had founded) took control of the cult and produced new legends and rituals to strengthen their corporate interests. Since the basilica and the abbey differed in their spiritualities, structures, and external ties, the canons and monks elaborated and manipulated Martin's cult in quite different ways. Farmer shows how one saint's cult lent itself to these varying uses, and analyzes the strikingly dissimilar Martins that emerged. Her skillful inquiry into the relationship between group identity and cultural expression illuminates the degree to which culture is contested territory. Farmer's rich blend of social history and hagiography will appeal to a wide range of medievalists, cultural anthropologists, religious historians, and urban historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aFrance. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501740602?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501740602zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter